title: For Sale/Trade:  Saiga 7.62x39 (AK type) rifle. Accepts AK high caps. Comes with 138Rnds and Tapco 6 Pos. Stock
postcontent:
For trade I have a Saiga 7.62x39 rifle. The saiga rifle is a 100% Russian manufactured AK with an altered design to allow importation into the U.S.

From the factory these rifles have a comb stock, and they cannot accept AK magazines. This rifle has the Tapco T6 AR style collapsible stock with pistol grip and a Dinzag arms bullet guide installed to allow for the use of more affordable and more common AKM-47 Magazines.

Saigas are the closest thing to a genuine Russian AK you can buy, they're even made in the same factory. 

This rifle has around 400 rounds through it. These sell new for around 350, while used this comes with the tapco stock, bullet guide and 138 rounds of 7.63x39. It does not, however, come with a magazine. AK mags are fairly easy to find.

Note: I will only sell to an Ohio resident over 18 years of age. with a valid state ID.

I can't travel more than an hour at any point this week, next week I can go farther.

Perfect for conceal carry. It's only 0.9 inches thick across the slide and super small, but still carries 6 - 9mm rounds. It definitely packs a lot of punch for it's size. title: For Sale:  Collectible Enfield WWII pistol
postcontent:
This is a British Enfield Number 2, Mark 1 .38-caliber revolver from World War II. The action (DAO) is very tight and completely functional. The black finish is original, complete, and without flaw. The original Bakelite grips are in immaculate condition. The cartridge ejector works fine and the barrel's grooves are still visible. Overall, this pistol would easily rate at 95%.

This webpage has some detailed history of the pistol: http://www.nrvoutdoors.com/ENFIELD%20SNUB/ENFIELD%20SNUB.htm. In the first photograph on the left margin (with the red velvet background), my pistol is almost identical to the one in the middle. However, my pistol has the distinction of having a factory-installed lanyard loop in the frame at the base of the grip, similar to the pre-WWII pistol pictured at the top. Research shows that this feature is quite rare and indicates that this particular pistol was a British officer's pistol which would have seen little, if any, battlefield usage. This would also account for this pistol's pristine condition.

Provenance from the early 1960s can be provided. The original Hunter leather holster is included in this sale as well as three (3) new 50-round boxes of .38 S&W Remington Express cartridges. Attached are photographs of my actual pistol.

My price is $750 negotiable or will trade straight-up for any generation Glock models 21, 21SF, 30, 30SF, 22, or 23 in very good to excellent condition.  Email me if you're interested.  Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Spencer 1865 carbine - great condition
postcontent:
1865 Spencer arms repeating rifle from private collection.

This excerpt taken from the blue book of gun values:
Previous manufacturer located in Boston, MA between 1860-1868. Spencer manufactured approximately 144,000 rimfire rifles and carbines, of which approximately 107,000 were contracted to the United States Government during the Civil War.  
The brainchild of young Christopher Miner Spencer, more than 13,500 Spencer M1860 Army rifles, 800 M1860 Navy rifles, and 48,000 M1860 Army carbines saw action during the Civil War.
In late 1864, the Chief of Ordnance directed modifications, including reducing the bore from .52 to .50 caliber, and shortening the barrel from 22 inches to 20 inches. The new carbine was designated the Spencer M1865 carbine. Nearly 19,000 were produced by the Spencer Repeating Rifle Company, and another 30,500 by the Burnside Rifle Company, although all were delivered too late to see action in the Civil War. Model 1865 carbines and refurbished M1860 carbines became the mainstay of America's troops on the Western Frontier until replaced by "Trap-Door" Springfield carbines after 1873.

 This one is in exceptional condition in metal and wood finish as well as bore.  I have a copy showing that the value should be somewhere between $5000-$7000.

title: For Sale:  Walther P22 with red dot scope
postcontent:
I have a Walther P22 pistol with a Walther brand Picatinny scope mount and a BSA red dot scope. The scope and mount are easily removed with one screw or the iron sights are still usable while the scope is mounted. The pistol comes with two factory magazines. I purchased the pistol brand new and before I even shot a single round with it I disassembled the gun for modifications and functional improvements. I've done a ton of work to this gun (too much to remember while writing this ad). The hours spent refining the gun would probably cost you $100 or more at the gunsmith. A few main points from memory:

- Removed 0.020" from the rear of the underside of the breech to reduce hammer drag

- Polished the extractor

- Radiused and polished the trigger bar ears as well as measuring them with calipers and then fine adjusting them to contact more of the slide

- Leveled the breach block and safety bar to lower the drag

- Re-profiled, squared and polished the hammer tip for smother operation

- Polished the feed ramp for better feeding (especially for hollow point ammo)

- Polished and peened the extractor and modified the extractor spring

- Fixed the safety lever for better operation (factory P22 safeties have a tendency to walk by themselves)

title: For Sale:  -SOLD- Custom AR-15/M4, Duracoat upper, many extras
postcontent:
I'm not sure where to start with this.
Not many AR-15/M4 rifles can be called unique. The modular, cookie-cutter nature of the platform kinda makes them all the same to some extent.
This one is about as original as you'll find, without commissioning a custom rifle from one of the boutique shops, and dropping several grand.
The gun itself is fairly basic internally. It's a Precision Aero lower, branded and sold by Surplus Ammo and Arms out of Washington State.
The upper is Mil-Spec M4 config, made in NC by Timberwolf Tactical.
16" barrel, 1:9 twist, M4 profile, M4 Feed ramps, A2 flash hider, Flat top with T-Marks.

The photos will give a better feel for the whole package, but here are the highlights:
- Full custom Duracoat finish on upper (including bolt carrier) in Magpul Dark Earth color.
- Full length (12.5") free floating quad rail with XTM 2-tone covers (plain rubber available if you prefer)
- Magpul MBUS flip up Front/Rear sights in Dark Earth
- Magpul MOE pistol grip, custom Duracoated in FDE (Flat Dark Earth, same as the upper)
- Magpul extended trigger guard, custom Duracoat FDE
- Magpul UBR stock system, custom Duracoat FDE
- Magpul (Genuine OEM) PMAG 20 round mag, custom Duracoat FDE
- Magpul RSA (Rail Sling Adapter) in Dark Earth
- Magpul AFG2 (Angled Foregrip) in Dark Earth
- Custom color fills on the safety selector pictograms. Red for fire, White for safe, HK-style.
- A little minor internal polishing and adjustment to clean up the trigger. Has zero creep and pulls lighter than most stock ARs.
- Polished M4 feed ramps to smooth up chambering under high fire rates.
- The scope and mount shown are NOT included, nor is the Bipod (both go with my varmint air rifle).
Both are for sale, just not included in the price.
- I also have a clone of an Aimpoint T-1 Micro Red Dot sight.
It drops on the rail nicely and looks sleek. I'll sell it for $75 extra.

**NOTE: Everything Magpul is Magpul PTS, unless otherwise specified. That's why it's $1,200 and not $2,000. :)
No PTS parts were used on internals or any parts of fire control.
Basically, it's only the furniture and cosmetic stuff that's PTS.

Not sure what else to say, I've spent MANY hours on this build.
The Duracoat process was by far the most complicated part of the build.
I tore down everything to individual parts, including disassembling the stock and other components, to ensure that everything was fully coated.
The gun was cured for a full 5 weeks before test firing to let the Duracoat harden. I used the new Duracoat SL on this build, which is supposed to be self-lubricating, and therefore more abrasion resistant. I have no idea if it works or not, that's just what Lauer Custom Weaponry (maker of Duracoat) claims.

Email with any additional questions.
Prefer FTF sale, but will ship upon receipt of payment via USPS money order or credit card (+3% charge). Buyer pays shipping and insurance via method of your choice.
Not really looking for trades, unless you have other rifles or handguns of interest. Even then, probably not. I need the money for other projects. :)
Feel free to ask, though. You might have something I really want.

title: For Sale:  Better than new Walther SP22 - M3 (Robocop gun)
postcontent:
As the title suggests, for sale is my Walther (actually S&W) SP22 - M3 model pistol, not to be confused with the P22 which is plagued by a slew of problems.  I bought this gun about 6 months ago and I've tons of fun with it.  I didn't plan on selling it but I want something in a larger caliber.  
  It's in better-than-new condition….I’ll explain.  When I got this gun I cleaned/oiled everything and went to shoot it for the first time.  I broke it in with 200 rounds of CCI minimag followed by 100 rounds of Winchester Super X and 100 rounds of Blazer followed by about 30 failed attempts with American Eagle.  I snaked the barrel every 100 rounds.  I was hoping it would shoot the AE but, sadly, I had more misfires than I had fires.  Oh well, the Blazer shoots as well as the MiniMags and it's just as cheap as AE.  When I got it home that night and stripped it there was a small gash in the finish on the side of the bolt-rail (see red arrow below) from several burrs on the bolt caused by the laser cutting of the stainless steel.  It should have been taken care of at the factory but apparently they all go out like that.  I just cleaned up the burrs with fine sandpaper, polished the bolt and it solved the problem.  I was gonna send it back to S&W on warranty for the gash but it's really just superficial and has no effect on performance.  I've put about 2000 rounds through it since then with zero problems.  After polishing the bolt it only took about 2/3 the force to cycle the action which felt kind of gritty from the factory.  I also polished the feed ramp and readjusted/polished the throats of the magazines which makes the rounds feed perfectly.   I've put a lot of care into this gun and you can tell when you shoot it.  It truly is better than new.  
  The M3 model has an upgraded match-grade 6" barrel (threaded and ready for a silencer) and a two-stage trigger that's fully adjustable for first-stage travel and force of pull.  These two features make this gun super-accurate and a pleasure to shoot.  The trigger stop is also adjustable.  It comes with two 10-round magazines, smooth rails for the top and bottom,  Picatinny rails for the top and bottom ($20) that allow for the use of any optics/laser combination, Tru-Glo sights ($30) and the original steel sights (both fully adjustable), extended European-style magazine release ($20), gun lock, tool kit, a key for the secondary lock and paperwork, all in a very nice foam-lined rugged plastic case.
   This gun is really easy to field-strip as well.  Unlike a Ruger MkIII or Buckmark that may require a hammer and/or engineering degree to take apart, you only have to remove 3 allen head screws to take this bad boy down.  I can strip it and put it back together in only 2 minutes.  
  My price is $375.   If you've done any research at all on these guns, you know you can't get an M1 model for this price after FFL fees and taxes.  Face to face only with valid identification.  You will be required to sign a bill of transfer.  I'd be happy to answer any questions you may have or send better pictures.  Thanks for looking.
